    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_report` row that
    declares the "Average Time to Close" single-score report on the
    `x_[scope]_case` custom table inside the scoped application `x_[scope]`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.1 (File-by-File Transformation Plan) verbatim:
        servicenow-case-management-poc/reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml
            CREATE  Source: -
            Key Changes: "Single-score: AVG(closed_date - opened_date) over
            Closed cases"

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning) verbatim:
        Manager View Dashboard widget inventory includes
            "single-score widget for Average time to close (computed as
             closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)"

    Per AAP Section 0.4.4 (User Interface Design) verbatim:
        Manager View Dashboard - "single-score widget for 'Average time
        to close' (computed as closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)"

    Per AAP Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework) verbatim, this report is
    one of the data sources for Gate 6 (Dashboards):
        "Both dashboards render with synthetic data ... All widgets display
         data; no broken report references"

    THIS FILE'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ===================================
    This is a `sys_report` record of type `single_score` with `aggregate=AVG`.
    It is the data source for a single tile on the Manager View dashboard
    (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml). The widget
    displays the AVERAGE elapsed time between when each case was opened
    (`opened_date`) and when it was closed (`closed_date`) over the
    population of cases whose `status` has reached the terminal value
    `Closed`.

    Among the eight reports in this folder, this is the most complex by
    a wide margin. The other seven aggregate over a single field with a
    simple aggregation (COUNT, GROUP BY, etc.) - this one aggregates over
    a date-difference computation. ServiceNow's `sys_report.aggregate=AVG`
    requires a single numeric `aggregation_source` field; it cannot
    natively express "AVG(field_a - field_b)" as a SQL expression. The
    standard ServiceNow pattern for this is to materialize the difference
    as a stored numeric column (Duration or Integer-seconds) on the parent
    table via a calculated field or business rule, then aggregate on that
    column.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE ANCHOR (READ-ONLY, NOT BYTE-FOR-BYTE PORTED)
    =================================================================
    ArkCase did not have a native "average time to close" report. The
    nearest source-side concept is the combination of:

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 168-173:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_created", nullable = false,
                    insertable = true, updatable = false)
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date created;
            @Column(name = "cm_case_closed")
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date closed;
        ArkCase tracked the case-creation timestamp (`created`, mapped to
        `cm_case_created`) and the case-closure timestamp (`closed`,
        mapped to `cm_case_closed`) on the same JPA entity. The pair is
        the input to any time-to-close calculation. The ServiceNow target
        renames `created` to `opened_date` and `closed` to `closed_date`
        per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim, but the semantic pairing is
        preserved.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/Disposition.java line 77-79:
            @Column(name = "cm_close_date")
            @Convert(converter = LocalDateConverter.class)
            private LocalDate closeDate;
        ArkCase's `Disposition` JPA entity carried a parallel `closeDate`
        for the case-disposition lifecycle (referenced by AAP Section
        0.2.1.1 as "Disposition record with closeDate, dispositionType,
        referExternalDate"). The ServiceNow POC consolidates ArkCase's
        bifurcated case-closure timestamps (CaseFile.closed plus
        Disposition.closeDate) into a single `closed_date` field on
        x_[scope]_case per AAP Section 0.3.2 minimal-change clause: the
        POC scope explicitly excludes a separate disposition-table.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseSummaryByStatusAndTime
        PeriodDto.java:
            private String timePeriod;
            private List<CaseByStatusDto> caseByStatusDtoList;
        ArkCase aggregated cases by status across time periods using a
        custom DTO consumed by Pentaho BI reports. The aggregator was
        Pentaho-side, NOT JPA-side. The ServiceNow target replaces
        Pentaho-driven time-period aggregation with platform-native
        sys_report records (this file plus the seven sibling reports in
        this folder), all powered by ServiceNow's native GlideAggregate
        engine instead of an external BI engine - per AAP Section 0.1.2
        ("Reporting transformation: Pentaho BI + Solr aggregates ->
        ServiceNow Reports + Performance Analytics-style dashboards").

    Note: the "true" ArkCase equivalent of THIS report (an
    AVG(closed - created) single number) would have been a Pentaho .prpt
    report file invoking a SQL `SELECT AVG(TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND,
    cm_case_created, cm_case_closed)) FROM acm_case_file WHERE
    cm_case_status = 'CLOSED'` - the Pentaho .prpt file is not in the
    repository (Pentaho artifacts are deployed via a separate Vagrant
    VM build per the README), so the source-side anchor is conceptual
    rather than file-based. The ServiceNow target's calculation is
    semantically equivalent: AVG over a duration-typed numeric column,
    filtered to cases at the terminal `Closed` status.

    THE OPTION C APPROACH (CHOSEN — POC LIMITATION)
    ================================================
    The original draft of this file used Strategy A — referencing a
    calculated field `duration_to_close_seconds` as the
    `<aggregation_source>`. That field, however, is NOT enumerated in
    AAP Section 0.4.1's dictionary directory tree, and adding it would
    require modifying the dictionary folder beyond the AAP-approved
    field set. Per AAP Section 0.7.2's Minimal-Change Clause and the
    "stop and report" instruction for capability gaps, the agent MUST
    NOT substitute an out-of-scope dictionary field; instead, the gap
    must be surfaced explicitly.

    This file therefore implements Option C: an EMPTY
    `<aggregation_source/>` element, accompanied by a clear capability-
    gap note here AND in `../docs/dashboards.md` Widget 4 description.
    Option C is the simplest fix that:
      - Respects AAP Section 0.7.2 "Minimal-Change Clause" — does not
        introduce an out-of-scope dictionary field;
      - Avoids substituting a column reference that does not exist
        in the deliverable Update Set, which would cause Gate 6 to
        report "broken report references" silently;
      - Aligns with AAP Section 0.7.2's "stop and report" requirement
        by EXPLICITLY surfacing the limitation in documentation rather
        than masking it via a graceful-fallback rationale.

    KNOWN POC LIMITATION (OPTION C)
    ===============================
    With `<aggregation_source/>` empty, the ServiceNow report engine
    has no numeric column to aggregate. The Manager View dashboard's
    "Average Time to Close" single-score widget will render either:
      - the platform's "No data" placeholder (most common rendering
        when AVG has no source column), or
      - the literal value 0 (in older platform releases that coerce
        an unbound aggregation to numeric zero).
    Either rendering communicates "POC limitation" rather than a
    spurious arithmetic value, and is non-blocking for Update-Set
    import or preview.

    REMEDIATION OPTIONS FOR FOLLOW-UP (DOCUMENTED, NOT IMPLEMENTED)
    ===============================================================
    Two follow-up paths could replace Option C with a meaningful
    aggregate; both require an explicitly-approved AAP amendment:

      Option A (calculated dictionary field):
        Add a new dictionary entry `x_[scope]_case_duration_to_close_seconds.xml`
        defining a calculated field on `x_[scope]_case` with type
        `integer` (or `duration` / `glide_duration` for human-readable
        display) and a calculation script equivalent to:

            (function calculatedFieldValue(current) {
                if (current.closed_date && current.opened_date) {
                    return gs.dateDiff(
                        current.opened_date.getDisplayValue(),
                        current.closed_date.getDisplayValue(),
                        true);
                }
                return 0;
            })(current);

        Then this report's `<aggregation_source/>` element would be
        re-populated with the new field's element name, and the
        widget would render an actual seconds-based AVG. This option
        is OUTSIDE current AAP §0.4.1 scope and is NOT applied here.

      Option B (Performance Analytics Indicator):
        Author a `pa_indicators` record + a scripted indicator source
        that computes `closed_date - opened_date` server-side and
        publishes a numeric indicator value. The widget's data source
        would change from `sys_report` to a Performance Analytics
        widget consuming the indicator. This option is OUTSIDE the
        AAP-enumerated reports/dashboards artifact set (§0.5.1) and
        is NOT applied here.

    Until either option is approved as an AAP amendment, the
    `<aggregation_source/>` element remains intentionally empty in
    this file and the limitation is documented at:

      - `../docs/dashboards.md` § "Widget 4: Average Time to Close"
      - the Manager View dashboard description in
        `../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml`
        comment block (no change to the dashboard XML itself —
        only Widget 4's source report is affected by this gap).

    SEMANTIC IMPACT ON VALIDATION GATE 6
    ====================================
    Validation Gate 6's pass condition is "All widgets display data;
    no broken report references". With Option C in effect, Widget 4
    on the Manager View dashboard renders "No data" rather than a
    numeric AVG. This is the documented POC limitation; the widget
    is NOT broken — its source report exists, has a valid filter and
    aggregate type, and lacks only an aggregation-source column. The
    rendering communicates "feature-gap" rather than "broken report".
    The remaining four Manager View widgets and all three Agent
    Workspace widgets render normally — Gate 6 passes for 7 of 8
    report references and is flagged as "POC limitation" for Widget 4.

    AAP CONSTRAINTS HONORED
    =======================
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity (AAP Section 0.7.2): `<name>` is
        prefixed `x_[scope]_`; `<table>` resolves to a scoped table;
        `<sys_scope>` and `<sys_package>` bind THIS record to the
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup; no global-
        scope writes are made. ALL artifact references resolve within
        the `x_[scope]` namespace.

      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids (AAP Section 0.7.2): the
        `<sys_scope>` and `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by
        scope name (`x_[scope]`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical record name `x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close`
        = 79fabb5f5754b629205b2382face3ebb) and is NOT a reference to
        any other record. The deterministic derivation makes the Update
        Set re-importable on a fresh PDI without sys_id collisions:
        re-importing the same XML on the same or any future PDI resolves
        the same sys_id and idempotently updates the same report row
        rather than creating a duplicate. This matches the sibling
        convention used by ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml
        (md5("x_[scope]_case") = bd806f5b23883f5d28ed792570f1070b) and
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml
        (md5("x_[scope]_case_manager") = 73710b052f274ece1d578c00f4424423).

      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP
        convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint");
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time and the Update-Set apply-time renaming propagates
        consistently across all bracketed placeholders in this artifact.

      - No PII (AAP Section 0.3.2 "No-PII constraint"): this record is
        a pure aggregation specification; it stores zero rows of case
        data, zero user identifiers, zero email addresses, zero
        organizational names. The report executes against the live case
        table at dashboard-render time; the data displayed there is the
        synthetic seed data authored under ../seed-data/cases/ per AAP
        Section 0.3.1.

      - No external integrations (AAP Section 0.3.2): the aggregation
        runs entirely on the platform's native GlideAggregate engine.
        No external BI tool (Pentaho, Tableau, PowerBI), no external
        analytics service, no external SQL execution layer. This is
        the AAP-prescribed transformation: ArkCase's Pentaho-driven
        analytics pipeline collapses into ServiceNow's native Reports +
        Dashboards stack.

      - Email-disabled (AAP Section 0.7.2): this report does NOT
        include any scheduled-email-delivery configuration. ServiceNow's
        sys_report supports a `is_scheduled` flag and integration with
        the email scheduler, but the POC explicitly disables email per
        AAP Section 0.7.2 ("Email notifications are disabled on the
        PDI"). The dashboard widget is the only consumer.

      - Single-Update-Set deliverable (AAP Section 0.7.2): this XML is
        one of the records that compose the final Update Set XML at
        ../update-set/x_[scope]_case_management_update_set.xml.

      - Minimal-Change Clause (AAP Section 0.7.2 / 0.3.2): no records
        beyond the AAP-enumerated set are introduced. The filter
        references the existing `status` field; the
        `<aggregation_source/>` element is intentionally LEFT EMPTY
        per Option C above, because no numeric duration column exists
        in the AAP-enumerated dictionary entries and adding one would
        violate the Minimal-Change Clause.

    FILTER SEMANTICS
    ================
    The `<filter>status=Closed</filter>` element uses ServiceNow's
    encoded-query string format. The semantics are:

      - `status` is the field name on `x_[scope]_case` (defined in
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_status.xml).
      - `=` is the encoded-query equality operator.
      - `Closed` is the Choice label literal as defined in
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml. The Title Case spelling
        ("Closed" - NOT "CLOSED" or "closed" or "CLOSE") MUST match
        the Choice list verbatim per AAP Section 0.1.2 (which preserves
        the AAP's Title Case Choice convention from Section 0.5.7
        "Data-Model Mapping").
      - The encoded-query string contains no special XML characters
        (=, alphabetic chars only) and requires no XML escaping.

    Why filter to Closed only:
      1) Cases in any non-Closed status have NULL closed_date by
         dictionary definition (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_closed_date.xml
         documents that closed_date is mandatory=false and is set ONLY
         on the Resolved -> Closed transition by
         ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_closed_date.xml). Aggregating
         over NULL durations either returns NULL (if the calculated
         field handles NULL coalescence) or coerces to 0 (the
         calculated-field calculation script returns 0 for non-Closed
         cases) - both corrupt the average.
      2) The semantic intent of "average time to close" is the average
         over the population of cases that HAVE BEEN CLOSED. Cases in
         Draft / Open / In Progress / Pending / Resolved are NOT YET
         CLOSED by definition; including them in the denominator would
         drag the average toward zero by treating
         not-yet-closed-but-eventually-will-close cases as instant
         closures.

    AGGREGATION SEMANTICS
    =====================
    With Option C in effect, the combination of
    `<aggregate>AVG</aggregate>`, an EMPTY `<aggregation_source/>`,
    and `<type>single_score</type>` produces an unbound AVG: the
    ServiceNow report engine has no numeric column to aggregate. At
    dashboard-render time, the widget displays "No data" (or 0 in
    older releases) rather than a numeric mean.

    If a future AAP amendment adopts Option A, the
    `<aggregation_source/>` element below would be re-populated with
    the new calculated-field element name (e.g.,
    `duration_to_close_seconds`), and the SQL-equivalent
    GlideAggregate query would become:

        SELECT AVG(duration_to_close_seconds)
        FROM   x_[scope]_case
        WHERE  status = 'Closed'

    producing a single seconds-based floating-point number. Until
    that amendment is approved, the empty `<aggregation_source/>`
    element is the AAP-correct treatment of the gap.

    DASHBOARD CONSUMPTION
    =====================
    The Manager View dashboard widget (in
    ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml) references
    THIS record by `name`:
      <widget>
        <report_name>x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close</report_name>
        ...
      </widget>
    NO sys_id reference - per AAP Section 0.7.2 "No-hardcoded-sys_id
    constraint" verbatim. The dashboard renders the single-score widget
    using the platform's native single-score-tile component.

    SEED DATA EXPECTATIONS (UNDER OPTION C)
    =======================================
    Under Option C, the widget will render "No data" regardless of
    whether the seed cases have `closed_date` populated, because the
    `<aggregation_source/>` is empty. Seed-data agents are not
    required to set realistic `opened_date`/`closed_date` deltas on
    the Closed demo cases solely for THIS report; the values remain
    semantically useful for the other Manager View widgets and for
    future Option A adoption. Per AAP Section 0.4.1 directory
    enumeration, the 10 demo cases include:
      x_[scope]_case_demo_06.xml (Closed, General Inquiry)
      x_[scope]_case_demo_10.xml (Closed, Complaint)
    Seed-data authors should still set realistic timestamps on these
    records (e.g., opened 10 days ago, closed 3 days ago — a 7-day
    duration) for downstream readiness when Option A is adopted, but
    THIS report's runtime output is unaffected by those values until
    `<aggregation_source/>` is re-populated.

    UPDATE SET DEPENDENCY ORDERING (AAP SECTION 0.5.2)
    ==================================================
    This record MUST load AFTER:
      - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml  (scoped app)
      - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml                (scope record)
      - ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml                  (parent table)
      - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_status.xml       (status field)
      - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_opened_date.xml  (opened_date field — referenced semantically only; not directly aggregated under Option C)
      - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_closed_date.xml  (closed_date field — referenced semantically only; not directly aggregated under Option C)
      - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml         (Closed Choice value)

    This record MUST load BEFORE:
      - ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml
        (Manager View dashboard widget references THIS report by name)

    Order within the reports folder is irrelevant since reports do
    not depend on one another.

